<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-05-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-05-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="186" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                        <head>No. 51.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Earl <persName type="from">Granville</persName> to Sir <persName type="to">E.
                                    Thornton</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Foreign
                                        Office</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-05-14"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 14,
                                1872</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p rend="center">[From British Blue Book “North America,” No. 9, (1872,) p.
                            20.]</p>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I asked General Schenck to-day whether it
                            would not be desirable to draught the identic note, to be addressed by
                            the British and United States Agents to the Arbitrators, communicating
                            to them the Treaty Article if it should be concluded.</p>
                        <p>General Schenck assented to this suggestion.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>GRANVILLE.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>